1	\chapter{Line bundles on schemes and the Picard group}
2	\label{chap:Picard_LineBundle}
3	
4	This chapter sets up the foundational Phase~B/C infrastructure: the type of \emph{line bundles} (invertible quasi-coherent sheaves) on a scheme $X$, the abelian-group structure under tensor product, and the pull-back functoriality. It is the smallest self-contained step toward the Picard scheme construction (Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable}) and feeds the Jacobian gap chain.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $\Pic_{C/k}$ in later phases.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}\leanok
11	[Line bundle on a scheme]
12	  \label{def:Scheme_LineBundle}
13	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.LineBundle}
14	  Let $X$ be a scheme. A \emph{line bundle} on $X$ is an invertible quasi-coherent $\mathcal O_X$-module: a sheaf $L$ of $\mathcal O_X$-modules that is quasi-coherent and locally free of rank $1$. Equivalently: an object of the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules that is invertible with respect to the tensor product $- \otimes_{\mathcal O_X} -$ in the symmetric monoidal category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules.
15	\end{definition}
16	
17	\paragraph{Status note (Phase C1, post-refactor).}
18	Following the Phase~C1 refactor (iter-109), the Lean body of \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.LineBundle} matches the geometric definition stated above. Concretely,
19	\[
20	  \mathrm{LineBundle}\,X \;:=\; \bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}\bigr)^{\!\times},
21	\]
22	the units of the (commutative) monoid structure on the skeleton of the symmetric monoidal category $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}). This mirrors the ring-side precedent $\mathrm{CommRing.Pic}\,R = \mathrm{Shrink}\bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,(\mathrm{SemimoduleCat}\,R)\bigr)^{\!\times}$ at \texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.PicardGroup:407}; the commutative-group structure derives from $\mathrm{Skeleton.instCommMonoid}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Monoidal.Skeleton:80}) followed by $\mathrm{instCommGroupUnits}$. No \texttt{Shrink} wrapper is needed: $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ already lives in $\mathrm{Type}\,(u+1)$, so $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ inhabits the same universe and the downstream \texttt{PicardFunctor}/\texttt{PicardFunctorAb} codomains have been bumped to match.
23	
24	\paragraph{Load-bearing transitive dependency on the monoidality of sheafification.}
25	The $\mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,(X.\mathrm{Modules})$ instance underlying the commutative-group structure is supplied by $\mathrm{Localization.Monoidal.Braided}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Localization.Monoidal.Braided:118}), which requires $W(X).\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$ for the sheafification class $W(X)$. This is the project's named-deferred sorry $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$ (\texttt{AlgebraicJacobian/Modules/Monoidal.lean:166}); see the load-bearing-disclosure paragraph in Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}. Post-C1, every theorem about $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$, $\Pic(X)$, $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctor}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctorAb}$, and the downstream Jacobian arc transitively consumes $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$; \texttt{lean\_verify} surfaces \texttt{sorryAx} in their axiom chains.
26	
27	\paragraph{Pull-back gap.}
28	Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback} below (and the associated functoriality lemmas $\mathrm{Pic.pullback\_id}$, $\mathrm{Pic.pullback\_comp}$) is currently sorry-bodied. The obstruction is a separate named-deferred Mathlib gap, recorded as Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj} below, asserting that the categorical pull-back functor $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$ is monoidal. The named-deferral route is chosen per analogist option~(c) of \texttt{analogies/c1-route.md}; see also the Phase~C1 row of \texttt{STRATEGY.md}.
29	
30	\begin{remark}
31	  Mathlib has the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules and the quasi-coherence typeclass. The combination ``invertible quasi-coherent sheaf'' is not pre-packaged; it is the content of this definition.
32	\end{remark}
33	
34	\section{Group structure under tensor product}
35	
36	% NOTE: post-C1 — the Lean body of `instCommGroupLineBundle` is `inferInstanceAs (CommGroup (Skeleton X.Modules)ˣ)` (no direct `sorry`), but the `CommGroup` instance transitively consumes `instIsMonoidal_W` (Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}); see the load-bearing-disclosure paragraph above.
37	\begin{theorem}\leanok
38	[Picard group of a scheme]
39	  \label{thm:Scheme_Pic_commGroup}
40	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.instCommGroupLineBundle}
41	  For every scheme $X$, the type of line bundles on $X$ (modulo isomorphism) carries a canonical commutative-group structure. The operation is tensor product over $\mathcal O_X$, the unit is the structure sheaf $\mathcal O_X$ itself, and the inverse of a line bundle $L$ is its $\mathcal O_X$-dual $L^\vee = \mathcal{H}om_{\mathcal O_X}(L, \mathcal O_X)$.
42	
43	  We denote this group by $\Pic(X)$ and call it the \emph{Picard group} of $X$.
44	\end{theorem}
45	
46	\begin{proof}
47	  \uses{def:Scheme_LineBundle, thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}
48	  \leanok
49	  Identifying $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ with $\bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}\bigr)^{\!\times}$ (the post-refactor body), the commutative-group structure is obtained by Lean's typeclass-resolution chain
50	  \[
51	    \mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,(X.\mathrm{Modules})
52	    \;\Longrightarrow\;
53	    \mathrm{CommMonoid}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules})
54	    \;\Longrightarrow\;
55	    \mathrm{CommGroup}\,\bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}\bigr)^{\!\times},
56	  \]
57	  via $\mathrm{Skeleton.instCommMonoid}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Monoidal.Skeleton:80}) followed by $\mathrm{instCommGroupUnits}$. The mathematical content "tensor product of invertible quasi-coherent sheaves is invertible quasi-coherent, with $\mathcal O_X$ as unit and the $\mathcal O_X$-dual as inverse" is packaged into $\mathrm{Skeleton.instCommMonoid}$ together with the localised-monoidal infrastructure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}); commutativity and associativity descend from the symmetric-monoidal structure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$.
58	\end{proof}
59	
60	\section{Pull-back functoriality}
61	
62	% NOTE: post-C1 — the Lean bodies of `Pic.pullback`, `Pic.pullback_id`, and `Pic.pullback_comp` are currently `sorry`, blocked on Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj} (a named-deferred Mathlib gap on the monoidality of the categorical pull-back functor on quasi-coherent $\mathcal O$-modules). The named-deferral route is analogist option~(c) of \texttt{analogies/c1-route.md}. `\leanok` on the statement block certifies that the declaration is well-formed and type-checks; closure of the proof body awaits Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}.
63	\begin{theorem}\leanok
64	[Pull-back of line bundles]
65	  \label{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}
66	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Pic.pullback}
67	  Let $f \colon X \to Y$ be a morphism of schemes. The categorical pull-back functor $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f \colon Y.\mathrm{Modules} \to X.\mathrm{Modules}$ induces a group homomorphism
68	  \[
69	    f^* \colon \Pic(Y) \;\to\; \Pic(X)
70	  \]
71	  by passing to invertible objects of the skeleton. Pull-back is contravariantly functorial: $(\mathrm{id}_X)^* = \mathrm{id}_{\Pic(X)}$ and $(f \circ g)^* = g^* \circ f^*$.
72	\end{theorem}
73	
74	\begin{proof}
75	  \uses{thm:Scheme_Pic_commGroup, thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}
76	  \leanok
77	  The eventual Lean definition is
78	  \[
79	    f^* \;=\; \mathrm{Units.map}\bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton.monoidHom}\,(\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f)\bigr),
80	  \]
81	  i.e.\ the units functor applied to the monoid homomorphism on skeletons induced by a monoidal functor (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Monoidal.Skeleton:111}). To form $\mathrm{Skeleton.monoidHom}$ on the categorical pull-back requires a $\mathrm{Functor.Monoidal}$ instance on $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$, which Mathlib b80f227 does not register. The project surfaces the missing iso as the named-deferred Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj} below. Once that iso is in hand the monoidality of the pull-back is mechanical: associativity and unit coherence reduce to standard sheaf-pullback functoriality, and $f^*$ on $\Pic$ is then the composite $\mathrm{Units.map} \circ \mathrm{Skeleton.monoidHom}$ applied to the resulting monoidal-functor structure. Pending closure (or a hand-construction equivalent) of Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}, the Lean bodies of $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$, $\mathrm{Pic.pullback\_id}$, and $\mathrm{Pic.pullback\_comp}$ remain \texttt{sorry}.
82	\end{proof}
83	
84	\section{Monoidality of the categorical pull-back functor (Mathlib gap)}
85	
86	% NOTE: post-C1 named-deferred Mathlib gap. The Lean body is `sorry`; `\leanok` on the statement block reflects only well-formedness of the introduced declaration. Closure awaits either a Mathlib refresh landing `(SheafOfModules.pullback _).Monoidal` or a hand-construction of the tensor-preservation iso.
87	\begin{theorem}\leanok
88	[Pull-back of $\mathcal O$-modules preserves tensor product]
89	  \label{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}
90	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.SheafOfModules.pullback_tensorObj}
91	  \uses{def:Modules_tensorObj}
92	  Let $f \colon X \to Y$ be a morphism of schemes and $M, N \in Y.\mathrm{Modules}$. Then the categorical pull-back functor $f^* := \mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$ preserves tensor products: there is a natural isomorphism
93	  \[
94	    f^*\bigl(M \otimes_{\mathcal O_Y} N\bigr) \;\cong\; f^* M \;\otimes_{\mathcal O_X}\; f^* N.
95	  \]
96	\end{theorem}
97	
98	\begin{proof}
99	  \uses{def:Modules_tensorObj, thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}
100	  \leanok
101	  This is the standard assertion that the inverse-image functor on $\mathcal O$-modules is monoidal. Mathlib provides $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$ as a functor on quasi-coherent $\mathcal O$-modules and has the corresponding statement on the presheaf side, but \texttt{b80f227} does not register a $\mathrm{Functor.Monoidal}\,(\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f)$ instance. The proof proceeds by the tensor-hom adjunction together with the fact that the pull-back of the structure-sheaf-unit map is again a unit map; see Stacks~\texttt{01AC} and \S5 of Hartshorne~II for the affine-local picture. A future Mathlib refresh that lands $(\mathrm{SheafOfModules.pullback}\,\_).\mathrm{Monoidal}$ collapses this obligation to the canonical $\mathrm{MonoidalCategoryStruct.tensorObj}$-comparison.
102	\end{proof}
103	
104	\section{Use in the project}
105	
106	The Picard group $\Pic(X)$ is the underlying \emph{set} (modulo isomorphism) of the Picard \emph{scheme} $\Pic_{C/k}$ in the curve case; the scheme structure adds a $k$-scheme of finite type representing the relative Picard functor $S \mapsto \Pic(C \times_k S) / \Pic(S)$.
107	
108	This chapter is therefore the gateway to:
109	\begin{itemize}
110	  \item Definition~\ref{def:Pic_functor} (Picard functor of $C/k$) --- quotient by $\Pic(S)$ uses Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}.
111	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable} (representability of the Picard scheme) --- uses the full $\Pic$ machinery built here.
112	  \item Definition~\ref{def:ofCurve} (Abel--Jacobi map) --- defined via the line bundle $\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)$ on $C \times C$, an explicit element of $\Pic(C \times C)$.
113	\end{itemize}
114	
115	Post-C1, all of these downstream consumers transitively depend on $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$ via the $\mathrm{CommGroup}$ instance on $\Pic(X)$ (load-bearing for $\mathrm{LineBundle}$, $\Pic$, $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctor}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctorAb}$, and the Jacobian framework); the $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$ arc additionally depends on Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}. Both dependencies surface in \texttt{lean\_verify}'s axiom chain.
116	
117	\section{Mathlib gap}
118	
119	Mathlib has:
120	\begin{itemize}
121	  \item The abelian category of sheaves of $\mathcal O_X$-modules on a scheme $X$, together with the (presheaf-side) symmetric monoidal structure and the sheafification machinery.
122	  \item Quasi-coherence as data on a sheaf of modules.
123	  \item The skeleton-of-a-monoidal-category construction $\mathrm{Skeleton}\,C$ and the chain $\mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,C \Longrightarrow \mathrm{CommMonoid}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,C) \Longrightarrow \mathrm{CommGroup}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,C)^{\!\times}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Monoidal.Skeleton}).
124	  \item The ring-side precedent $\mathrm{CommRing.Pic}\,R = \mathrm{Shrink}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,(\mathrm{SemimoduleCat}\,R))^{\!\times}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.PicardGroup:407}).
125	  \item The categorical pull-back functor $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$ on quasi-coherent $\mathcal O$-modules (\texttt{Mathlib.AlgebraicGeometry.Modules.Sheaf}).
126	\end{itemize}
127	
128	What is missing and supplied by this chapter:
129	\begin{itemize}
130	  \item The scheme-side $\mathrm{CommGroup}\,(\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X)$ instance, threading the skeleton-units idiom through $X.\mathrm{Modules}$. Transitively load-bearing on $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$ (Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}) for the required $\mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,(X.\mathrm{Modules})$.
131	  \item A scheme-morphism-functorial pull-back homomorphism $\Pic(Y) \to \Pic(X)$, currently sorry-bodied (Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}).
132	  \item The monoidality iso $f^*(M \otimes N) \cong f^* M \otimes f^* N$ for the categorical pull-back on $\mathcal O$-modules, recorded as the named-deferred Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}. Mathlib b80f227 has the analogous monoidality on the presheaf-side pushforward (\texttt{PresheafOfModules.PushforwardZeroMonoidal}) but no $\mathrm{Functor.Monoidal}$ instance for the pull-back of sheaves of modules.
133	\end{itemize}
134	
135	These are mapped to Phase~B/C step~1 of the project strategy. See also the cross-referenced load-bearing-disclosure paragraph in Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal} on $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$.
136

